ists of donors) and Muslim Arabic sources (biographical dictionaries, historical and geographical literature). The practitioners come from various socio-economic strata and lived in urban as well as rural locations in Muslim countries.Both the biographies and the accompanying discussion shed light on various views and aspects of the medicine practised in this period by Muslim, Jews and Christians, as well as issues such as professional, daily and personal lives; successes and failures; families; Jewish communities; and inter-religious affairs.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aJewish physicianszIslamic countriesvBiography. 0aJewish physicianszIslamic countriesxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aMedicine, MedievalzIslamic countries. 4aIslamic Studies. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311078040640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978147448400840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474484008423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781474484008/original  a978-3-11-078040-6  Edinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK